No lady. I DO want highly trained killers in my city's police force. You don't measure up, and should never have been hired as a policeman. We just don't need you. Please find a real job.

I need violent MEN to take down vicious criminals and bandits. And maybe removing clearly impaired drivers from our streets. And to get this, I'm willing to grant some discretion on how the officer carries out these tasks. Most people would agree with this concept IF we could keep you damn people chained.

Instead, most police act like attack dogs without leashes. Going after 5 year olds instead of "bad guys". That's why police are in this place. Not because of Floyd. Police earned this.

See you nabbed 16 million views from your "heartfelt video". Posting ANYTHING to twitter or youtube should have gotten you fired. It is the measure of police departments infestation with poseurs that your act didn't.

We need a LOT fewer cops and ZERO Staceys. Just fact. And if police can't get their act together soon, many will elect to rely on paid assassins to get these tasks done. Police? Been there, tried that...didn't work very well. Ticket punchers all.

posts.body:
>>b2a0c273-4008-48b8-9e67-6ce5d5ca9aef
Zeronet is a public system. There are always tradeoffs for that.

If you use it only via Tor - you're still very safe. Consider that your browser is just a readout, with the Zeronet server doing "all the talking" via a six hop Tor circuit.

Barring a no knock raid where they seize all your hardware - there is no means for anyone to identify you. And if you keep your system on a disk with full disk encryption - getting anything becomes a high bar indeed.

Numerous deficiencies have been discovered with hardware disk encryption systems, but software FDE is now well tested and very robust.

LUKS is good for Linux
Diskcryptor works well for Windows.

I'm sure the Mac people have something equivalent.

Never let the perfect be the enemy of the good. Once you learn the gotchas on ZeroNet - it's a very robust and simple system. The one thing it really lacks right now is a search engine - and that might be damn difficult. Unless site owners submit their address for crawling - nothing will ever be known about them. Onion sites have this same problem.

I'm certain better decentralized schemes will arise, but ZeroNet still retains a fundamental virtue. It's simple. Simple things are hard to screw up.

>>b7597d0d-848f-4cb4-a682-f58ad69284fa
ZeroID and all the server rebooting required to get it working is really the Achilles heel of ZeroNet. Many new users will just give up - never realizing how close they came.
